In article <2v99sb$bo8@news.delphi.com>,
ANSPRING@DELPHI.COM <anspring@news.delphi.com> wrote:
>Alice wishes to send a single plaintext block P.  
>She computes ENCRYPT(K1, P^IV1) = C;
>She then selects a dummy message D and computes 
>IV2 = DECRYPT(K2,C)^D;  She then transmits IV2,C.
>	
>Bob receives IV2 and C, discards IV2 and computes 
>DECRYPT(K1,C)^IV1 = P, using the previously agreed upon IV.

A slight simplification: Alice and Bob agree on a key K1.  Alice
computes IV = P XOR K1 and C = IV XOR Encrypt(K2, D).  Alice
then transmits IV, C to Bob.  Bob then gets the real message P
by computing IV XOR K1, and gives the Authorities K2 to reveal
the dummy message D by a standard CBC decryption.  This saves
having to securely transmit IV1, and simplifies Bob's recovery
of P.

		--Ken Pizzini
